lumage is the one that differs most from Cherrie's tanager. Immatures have an orange tint to the underparts and rump, and look like a paler and duller female Cherrie's tanager. The Passerini's tanager's call is a sharp wac. Its song consists of a few clear pleasant notes, delivered in shorter phrases than that of its Pacific relative. Ecology It is very common from sea level to 1200 m altitude, and occurs occasionally up to 1700 m. The preferred habitat is semi-open areas including light second growth, woodland edges, gardens and pasture with bushes. Passerini's tanagers occur in pairs, small groups, or as part of a mixed-species feeding flock, and up to a dozen birds may roost together in dense thickets at night. This species feeds on certain small fruit, usually swallowed whole, insects and spiders. The cup nest is built up to 6 m high in a tree. The normal clutch is two pale blue or grey eggs, marked with black, brown or lilac. This species will sometimes raise two broods in a season References Further reading", "shortSummary": "The scarlet-rumped tanager (Ramphocelus passerinii) is a medium-sized passerine bird. This tanager is a resident breeder in the Caribbean l…", "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6a/Ramphocelus_passerinii_%28male%29.jpg/960px-Ramphocelus_passerinii_%28male%29.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-ramphocelus", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-ramphocelus-passerinii", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-ramphocelus", "species": "taxonomy-species-ramphocelus-passerinii"}, "expandable": true, "x": 44.36, "y": -720.43, "z": 370.29}, {"id": "taxonomy-genus-ramphocelus", "name": "Ramphocelus", "latinName": "Ramphocelus", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "genus", "summary": "Ramphocelus（Ram